## 1. Design Goals

- Provide a low-friction first complete flow on the key page
- Prioritize clear feedback, visible state, and recoverable errors

## 2. System Boundary

- Inputs: browser visits, navigation, form input, button clicks
- Outputs: rendered pages, interaction feedback, notifications, status display
- External systems: backend APIs, auth systems, analytics or monitoring
- Outside the system: complex operations workflows, heavy offline computation

## 3. Architecture Overview

[Describe the browser-side structure as page shell -> feature modules -> data access layer, and note the key state flows.]

## 3.1 Candidate Options and User Confirmation

| Topic | Option | Advantages | Costs / Risks | Recommendation | Confirmed by user |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Page delivery model | SPA | Flexible interactions and direct frontend state control | First-load performance and SEO may be weaker | Usually suitable for dashboard-style products | [yes / no] |
| Page delivery model | SSR / SSG / Hybrid | Better first-load behavior, SEO, or content delivery | Higher build and deployment complexity | Suitable for content-heavy or first-load-sensitive products | [yes / no] |

If this section is still unresolved, do not treat the page delivery model as final.

## 4. Module Design

| ID | Module | Responsibility | Requirements |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DES-001` | Page shell and route entry | Provides navigation, layout skeleton, and first-screen entry points | `FR-001` |
| `DES-002` | Core interaction flow and state feedback | Handles forms, async state, errors, and success feedback | `FR-001`, `FR-002` |

## 5. Data and State

- Core entities: page view state, form draft, remote data snapshot
- Key fields: loading state, error message, user input, latest result
- State transitions: empty -> loading -> success / failure -> retry or continue

## 6. Interfaces and Contracts

| Interface | Input | Output | Failure modes | Requirements |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| [Page action] submit key form | User input and page context | Success feedback, refreshed state, next-step entry | validation failure, network failure, permission failure | `FR-001`, `FR-002` |

## 7. Technical Decisions and Trade-Offs

- Decision: prefer a clear page layering model and explicit state management
- Alternatives: place all logic directly inside page components
- Why not chosen: interaction, state, and error handling would become difficult to maintain

Record important decisions in `docs/adr/` when appropriate.

